{"body":"## Status\n\n☐ SC-1 ☐ SC-2 ☐ SC-3 ☐ SC-4 ☐ SC-5 ☐ SC-6 ☐ SC-7 ☐ SC-8 ☐ SC-9\n\n## Root Cause\n\nAuditor agent cards (`.opencode/agents/auditor-*.md`) are identical mechanical shells: *\"evaluate whether another AI agent's output satisfies specific criteria.\"* Sub-agents receive no intelligence posture instructions, no clean room violation detection protocol, no audit phase context. They're treated as simple evaluation units rather than intelligent adversarial agents. This produces three failures:\n\n1. **No audit phase awareness** — an auditor evaluating a spec vs. a plan-fidelity auditor vs. an implementation auditor all share the same generic posture\n2. **No semantic depth** — auditors perform mechanical checklisting rather than exploring full semantic range and conflict avenues\n3. **No clean room defense** — auditors proceed with tainted dispatch context because they have no protocol to detect it\n\n## Fix Approach\n\nThree-layer architecture: generic agent cards at the base, phase-specific context injected at dispatch, phase-specific procedures in SKILL.md task files.\n\n```\nLayer 1: Agent cards (.opencode/agents/auditor-*.md)  ← Generic adversarial posture\nLayer 2: SKILL.md dispatch context                    ← audit_phase + phase-specific criteria\nLayer 3: SKILL.md task files                          ← Phase-specific procedures\n```\n\n**Ownership boundaries:**\n- **Orchestrator** owns dispatch context integrity (no leaked reasoning into auditor context)\n- **Agent card** owns self-audit (the card's MANDATORY FIRST CHECK protocol detects context tampering before any audit work begins)\n- **SKILL.md task files** own phase-specific verification procedures (what to check, how deeply, against what reference)\n- **Violation of any boundary** = poisoned pipeline per `000-critical-rules.md` §Orchestrator Inline Work = Poisoned Pipeline. The auditor's CONTEXT_TAINTED refusal is the first line of defense — it halts before tainted work propagates.\n\n## Success Criteria\n\n| SC | Description |\n|---|---|\n| SC-1 | All 9 auditor agent cards include a MANDATORY FIRST CHECK for clean room violation detection. Violation signals are explicitly defined: (1) **Expected outcomes** — phrases like \"should find X\", \"expect Y to pass\", \"the answer is Z\"; (2) **Pre-determined file paths** — any file path in dispatch context beyond \"read spec #N\"; (3) **Orchestrator reasoning** — sentences like \"I think\", \"based on my analysis\", \"the issue appears to be\"; (4) **Cached/prior results** — references to other auditors, prior sessions, \"as noted in the last audit\"; (5) **Implementation context** — code snippets, execution logs, or implementation notes. On detection, auditor MUST return `status: CONTEXT_TAINTED` with specific violations listed, and MUST refuse to proceed — proceeding with tainted context produces poisoned work that must be discarded per `000-critical-rules.md` §Discard on Sub-Agent Failure |\n| SC-2 | All 9 auditor agent cards include a semantic depth mandate. The mandate is operationally defined via boundary examples — **Mechanical (FORBIDDEN)**: (a) checking if string X exists in file Y, (b) confirming field count matches, (c) grepping for keyword \"PASS\", (d) counting SCs against plan phases. **Semantic (REQUIRED)**: (a) verifying string X means the same thing in context as the spec intends, (b) confirming each field's purpose is non-redundant and its absence would create an unverifiable gap, (c) evaluating whether a PASS verdict's evidence artifact actually proves the claim, (d) verifying each SC-to-phase mapping semantically (does Phase 3's \"update dispatch\" SC actually mean updating dispatch, or was the phase miscategorized?). Mechanical-only audit is a critical violation per SC-7 |\n| SC-3 | All 9 auditor agent cards require a `clean_room` block in their output format with three fields: `verified` (boolean — true only if no violation signals detected), `violations_detected` (array of strings — each is an excerpt from the dispatch context that matched a violation signal), `dispatch_context_hash` (string — SHA-256 of the serialized dispatch context for post-execution integrity verification) |\n| SC-4 | All 9 auditor agent cards remain generic — they accept `audit_phase` from dispatch context rather than being pre-wired for a specific phase. Current agent cards are already identical (confirmed: all 9 have the same 34-line body differing only in frontmatter model field). The spec preserves this genericity while adding intelligence posture and clean room defense |\n| SC-5 | Each audit SKILL.md (spec-auditor, plan-fidelity-auditor, concern-separation-auditor, coherence-auditor, adversarial-audit) declares its audit phase identity in its Persona section and Operating Protocol. None currently do (confirmed: spec-auditor Persona says \"Content-Aware Audit Orchestrator\" without phase; plan-fidelity-auditor, concern-separation-auditor, coherence-auditor lack phase identity; adversarial-audit has dispatch protocol but no explicit phase declaration) |\n| SC-6 | All skills that dispatch auditor sub-agents include `audit_phase` in dispatch context, with a value from: `spec`, `plan_fidelity`, `concern_separation`, `coherence`, `implementation`, `adversarial_verification`. This includes: approval-gate, divide-and-conquer, executing-plans, finishing-a-development-branch, writing-plans, verification-before-completion, and adversarial-audit. Note: the `implementation` phase has no dedicated auditor SKILL.md — it is handled contextually by verification-before-completion and finishing-a-development-branch which dispatch auditors during post-implementation verification with `audit_phase: implementation` |\n| SC-7 | Add critical violation `critical-rules-046` to `000-critical-rules.md` after §Verification Dishonesty (after `critical-rules-009`), with title \"Mechanical-only audit without full semantic and conflict exploration is prohibited\", conditions: `audit_performed_via_keyword_match_only == true OR conflict_avenues_explored == false`, actions: `HALT, RE-DISPATCH_WITH_SEMANTIC_DEPTH_INSTRUCTION`. Enforcement: (1) behavioral test per SC-8/SC-9, (2) yaml+symbolic rule `critical-rules-046`, (3) content-verification tag check for `semantic-depth` in agent card bodies |\n| SC-8 | BEHAVIORAL enforcement test (`auditor-context-tainted-refusal.sh`) dispatches an auditor with intentionally tainted dispatch context containing (a) an expected outcome phrase, (b) a pre-determined file path, and (c) orchestrator reasoning. Test verifies auditor returns `CONTEXT_TAINTED` in its output and refuses to proceed with audit work. This is behavioral (tests actual model response to tainted input) rather than content-verification (checking file contents) because the test validates that the AI model itself detects and refuses the bias — a file-level check cannot verify model behavior |\n| SC-9 | BEHAVIORAL enforcement test (`auditor-semantic-exploration.sh`) dispatches an auditor with a plan-spec pairing where the plan says \"update all dispatch context schemas to include audit_phase\" but the spec's Files Affected table only lists `approval-gate/SKILL.md` — not `divide-and-conquer/SKILL.md`, `executing-plans/SKILL.md`, `finishing-a-development-branch/SKILL.md`, or `writing-plans/SKILL.md`, all of which also dispatch sub-agents and would need `audit_phase`. Mechanical grep: finds \"dispatch\" in all 5 files → PASS (no conflict detected). Semantic exploration: discovers the plan's \"all dispatch context schemas\" claim contradicts the spec's incomplete Files Affected table → FAIL (4 files missing from scope). Test verifies auditor identifies this gap |\n\n## Files Affected\n\n| File | Change |\n|---|---|\n| `.opencode/agents/auditor-deepseek-v4.md` | Add clean room protocol, semantic depth mandate, CONTEXT_TAINTED refusal, clean_room output field |\n| `.opencode/agents/auditor-deepseek-v3.md` | Same |\n| `.opencode/agents/auditor-deepseek-flash.md` | Same |\n| `.opencode/agents/auditor-glm-5.md` | Same |\n| `.opencode/agents/auditor-glm-5.1.md` | Same |\n| `.opencode/agents/auditor-qwen3.5.md` | Same |\n| `.opencode/agents/auditor-kimi-k2.md` | Same |\n| `.opencode/agents/auditor-devstral-2.md` | Same |\n| `.opencode/agents/auditor-mistral-large.md` | Same |\n| `.opencode/skills/spec-auditor/SKILL.md` | Add audit phase identity, phase-specific semantic instructions |\n| `.opencode/skills/plan-fidelity-auditor/SKILL.md` | Add audit phase identity, phase-specific semantic instructions |\n| `.opencode/skills/concern-separation-auditor/SKILL.md` | Add audit phase identity, phase-specific semantic instructions |\n| `.opencode/skills/coherence-auditor/SKILL.md` | Add audit phase identity, phase-specific semantic instructions |\n| `.opencode/skills/adversarial-audit/SKILL.md` | Add audit phase identity, ensure dispatch context includes audit_phase |\n| `.opencode/skills/approval-gate/SKILL.md` | Add audit_phase to dispatch context schema |\n| `.opencode/skills/divide-and-conquer/SKILL.md` | Add audit_phase to dispatch context schema |\n| `.opencode/skills/executing-plans/SKILL.md` | Add audit_phase to dispatch context schema |\n| `.opencode/skills/finishing-a-development-branch/SKILL.md` | Add audit_phase to dispatch context schema |\n| `.opencode/skills/writing-plans/SKILL.md` | Add audit_phase to dispatch context schema |\n| `.opencode/skills/verification-before-completion/SKILL.md` | Add audit_phase to dispatch context schema (receives `audit_phase: implementation` when dispatching auditors) |\n| `.opencode/guidelines/000-critical-rules.md` | Add critical-rules-046: mechanical-only audit violation |\n| `.opencode/tests/behaviors/auditor-context-tainted-refusal.sh` | NEW — behavioral test for SC-8 |\n| `.opencode/tests/behaviors/auditor-semantic-exploration.sh` | NEW — behavioral test for SC-9 |\n| `.opencode/tests/behaviors/phase3-auditor-infra-fix.sh` | UPDATE — agent card output format change (clean_room block) |\n| `.opencode/tests/behaviors/clean-room-test-dispatch.sh` | UPDATE — dispatch context schema change (audit_phase) |\n| `.opencode/tests/behaviors/clean-room-structural-verify.sh` | UPDATE — dispatch context schema change |\n| `.opencode/tests/behaviors/clean-room-implementation-dispatch.sh` | UPDATE — dispatch context schema change |\n| `.opencode/tests/behaviors/clean-room-git-workflow-dispatch.sh` | UPDATE — dispatch context schema change |\n| `.opencode/tests/behaviors/model-aware-clean-room-dispatch.sh` | UPDATE — dispatch context schema change |\n| `.opencode/tests/behaviors/adversarial-audit-skill-exists.sh` | UPDATE — agent card content change |\n\n## Implementation Plan\n\n1. Agent card body template — draft the enhanced prompt body, validate it's generic enough for all phases\n2. Apply to all 9 agent cards — identical body across all cards\n3. Update spec-auditor SKILL.md — audit phase identity + semantic instructions + audit_phase in dispatch\n4. Update plan-fidelity-auditor SKILL.md — same\n5. Update concern-separation-auditor SKILL.md — same\n6. Update coherence-auditor SKILL.md — same\n7. Update adversarial-audit SKILL.md — ensure cross-validate passes audit_phase to dispatched auditors\n8. Update approval-gate SKILL.md — add audit_phase to dispatch context\n9. Update divide-and-conquer, executing-plans, finishing-a-development-branch, writing-plans, verification-before-completion SKILL.md — add audit_phase to dispatch context\n10. Add critical-rules-046 to 000-critical-rules.md — mechanical-only audit = violation\n11. Create BEHAVIORAL test: auditor-context-tainted-refusal — RED phase test\n12. Create BEHAVIORAL test: auditor-semantic-exploration — RED phase test\n13. Update existing behavioral tests (phase3-auditor-infra-fix, clean-room-*.sh, adversarial-audit-skill-exists) for new output format / dispatch schema\n14. Run both new behavioral tests to confirm RED — they should fail before implementation\n15. Implement items 1-10 — GREEN phase\n16. Run both new behavioral tests to confirm GREEN — verify passing\n17. Run updated existing behavioral tests — verify no regressions\n18. Run content-verification test — confirm rule text exists in agent cards and guidelines\n\n## Audit Trail\n\n- **Round 1** (GLM-5.1 + Mistral-Large): overall_consensus = FAIL. Prompt wording caused Mistral to evaluate implementation state rather than spec quality. All SCs failed due to misframing.\n- **Round 2** (Qwen3.5 + Kimi-K2): overall_consensus = FAIL. GAP-1 only — Kimi-K2 identified that `verification-before-completion/SKILL.md` was missing from Files Affected despite SC-6 referencing it for `audit_phase: implementation`. All other criteria passed consensus.\n- **Round 3** (pending): After adding verification-before-completion/SKILL.md to Files Affected and clarifying SC-6 scope.\n\n🤖 Co-authored with AI: OpenCode (ollama-cloud/glm-5.1)","title":"[SPEC-FIX] Intelligent Audit Dispatch — Audit Phase Identity, Semantic Depth, and Clean Room Protocol"}
